On Hostinger (and most CPanel/LSCache environments), your public_html and gov_id folders usually sit side-by-side in the root directory.

To save files there, you must use the absolute server path to move the file, but since that folder is "above" public_html, it is not accessible via a standard browser URL.

Here is how you handle both the saving and the viewing:

1. The PHP Logic Update
You need to define two paths: one for the server to move the file (PATH) and one for the browser to "see" it. Since browsers cannot go above public_html, we will use a small "viewer" trick.

Replace your current upload block with this:

PHP

if (isset($_FILES['image']) && $_FILES['image']['error'] === 0) {
    // 1. Define the absolute path to gov_id (one level up from public_html)
    $server_root = dirname(__DIR__); // Goes from public_html/project to public_html, then to root
    $upload_dir = $server_root . '/gov_id/'; 
    
    if (!is_dir($upload_dir)) mkdir($upload_dir, 0775, true);

    $filename = time() . '_' . $_FILES['image']['name'];
    $target = $upload_dir . $filename;

    if (move_uploaded_file($_FILES['image']['tmp_name'], $target)) {
        // 2. Store a reference that we can use to fetch the file later
        // We store the filename only, or a relative indicator
        $img_path = 'fetch_file.php?name=' . urlencode($filename); 
    }
}
2. The "Viewer" Script (fetch_file.php)
Since gov_id is private (outside public_html), your <img> tags will break if you point them there directly. Create a file named fetch_file.php inside your public_html folder:

PHP

<?php
session_start();
// Security: Only allow logged-in users or active sessions to view
if (!isset($_SESSION['step'])) exit; 

$filename = $_GET['name'] ?? '';
$path = dirname(__DIR__) . '/gov_id/' . basename($filename);

if (file_exists($path)) {
    $mime = mime_content_type($path);
    header("Content-Type: $mime");
    readfile($path);
    exit;
}
?>
3. Folder Permissions on Hostinger
For this to work, the gov_id folder needs to allow the webserver to write to it.

Log into your Hostinger HPanel.

Go to File Manager.

Right-click the gov_id folder.

Select Permissions.

Ensure it is set to 755 (or 775 if 755 fails).

Summary of the Flow
Storage: The file moves to .../gov_id/image.jpg (Safe from public browsing).

Database/Session: The path is stored as fetch_file.php?name=image.jpg.

Display: When the chat renders <img src="fetch_file.php?name=image.jpg">, the viewer script grabs the file from the private folder and serves it safely.

